<!-- Val -->
	<section xml:id="ref.expressions.val">
		<title>Val</title>
		<section xml:id="ref.expressions.val.body">
			<para>
The declaration <code>val x = G</code>, followed by expression <code>F</code>, is 
actually just a different way of writing the expression <code><![CDATA[F <x< G]]></code>.
Thus, <code>val</code> shares all of the behavior of the pruning combinator. (This is also true when a pattern is used instead
of variable name <code>x</code>).
</para>
		</section>
		
		<section xml:id="ref.expressions.val.examples">
		  <title>Examples</title>

		  <example xml:id="ref.expressions.val.examples.one"><title>One Two Sum</title>
<programlisting><![CDATA[
{- Assign 3 to x and 6 to y -}
val x = 1 + 2
val y = x + x
]]></programlisting>
		  </example>
	  </section>
		
